3862	\label{lemma-cofinal-systems-coverings-standard-case}
3863	Let $X$ be a topological space. Let $\mathcal{B}$ be a basis for the
3864	topology on $X$. Assume that for every triple $U, U', U'' \in \mathcal{B}$
3865	with $U' \subset U$ and $U'' \subset U$ we have $U' \cap U'' \in \mathcal{B}$.
3866	For each $U \in \mathcal{B}$, let $C(U) \subset \text{Cov}_\mathcal{B}(U)$
3867	be a cofinal system.
3868	Let $\mathcal{F}$ be a presheaf of sets on $\mathcal{B}$.
3869	The following are equivalent
3870	\begin{enumerate}
3871	\item The presheaf $\mathcal{F}$ is a sheaf on $\mathcal{B}$.
3872	\item For every $U \in \mathcal{B}$ and every covering
3873	$\mathcal{U} : U = \bigcup U_i$ in $C(U)$ and for every
3874	family of sections $s_i \in \mathcal{F}(U_i)$ such
3875	that $s_i|_{U_i \cap U_j} = s_j|_{U_i \cap U_j}$ there
3876	exists a unique section $s \in \mathcal{F}(U)$ which
3877	restricts to $s_i$ on $U_i$.
3878	\end{enumerate}
3879	\end{lemma}
3880	
3881	\begin{proof}
3882	This is a reformulation of
3883	Lemma \ref{lemma-cofinal-systems-coverings} above
3884	in the special case where the coverings $\mathcal{U}_{ij}$
3885	each consist of a single element. But also this case is much
3886	easier and is an easy exercise to do directly.
3887	\end{proof}
